{"id":8605,"date":"2021-10-01T18:19:03","date_gmt":"2021-10-01T22:19:03","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/?p=8605"},"modified":"2021-10-01T18:19:04","modified_gmt":"2021-10-01T22:19:04","slug":"article-the-big-picture-a-brief-history-of-the-u-s-debt-ceiling","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/article-the-big-picture-a-brief-history-of-the-u-s-debt-ceiling\/","title":{"rendered":"The Big Picture: A Brief History of the U.S. Debt Ceiling"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The U.S. debt ceiling has once again emerged as a top concern of investors, but just how worried they should be all depends on when and whether the United States Congress can negotiate a plan to raise or suspend the country\u2019s debt limit and save the U.S. Treasury from the sure-fire catastrophe of default. Here is a brief \u201cby the numbers\u201d history of the ceiling and what might be in play for it and equity markets moving forward.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1000\" height=\"217\" src=\"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-01-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8622\" srcset=\"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-01-1.png 1000w, https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-01-1-300x65.png 300w, https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-01-1-768x167.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"Fineprint\">Source: The U.S. Department of the Treasury<\/div><br>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-default\"\/>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1000\" height=\"221\" src=\"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-02-2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8623\" srcset=\"https:\/\/perspectives.agf.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/tbp-debt-ceiling-e-0